The diet of an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes carcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren weigh above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models around him is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, carcuterie is found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of the obese had fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with a awareness action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of young adults, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today – only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 students from the primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third grade have signed up for this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed indicate, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast—in case —breakfast —taste — dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and meatballs at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes a few basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the families of the students eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone takes their own breakfast.
And the worst thing that has been found is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children, unhealthy fries are more often consumed.
Almost every student – not to mention weight – drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports regularly, but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food based on opportunities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are a lot of cakes, meat and sweets.
“The most alarming thing is especially a great preference for sweet lemonade,” the survey found.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want any feculants at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Head on Health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the awareness session "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a strong desire to focus on healthy eating," the results of the survey said.
For example, the most notable was for sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children have most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sugary dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of breadballs or potatoes).
