IBM History: From slices of cheese to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York City a hundred years ago; it originally had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then shadowed the firm’s founder – it was Watson’s ideas that so far have been based on the identity and culture of society.
Watson led the firm almost in 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson’s leadership, revenue increased to $9 million and the firm’s expansion began in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family, the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer factory to Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company from Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of advice and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept “a smarter planet”.
Its objective is the intelligent utilization of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
As far as the business area is concerned, IBM recently developed a “Smarter Commerce” platform that helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history on our territory.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 and was the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
