How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a westward inclination and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter or the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the West however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling west was rejected by “politically incorrect” people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs were buying and this habit lasts until now.
The travels of the Czechs have been a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were the maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of vacation in countries around the world.
The big paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in neighbouring Western countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with you its own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased, which has led to another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter flights that through contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to what existed before.
In the late 90s of the last century, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the US which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the far warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully fit into the group of developed countries.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including the attached charges.
