Here he wrote an unusual book that he describes, with accuracy, as "a work of anti-history."
It has a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, that a "book describing what it might look like." We find the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from both sides of the war, from young schoolchildren and botanists to climbers, through doctors, ambulances and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose their members, become mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives here fluctuate like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are re-enlightened.
Peter Englund's book differs from traditional history books.
It brings a denial to the idea that the First World War is only summed up by the terrible war of trenches on the Western front.
"Beauty and Grief" skillfully describes other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; a Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsé-tsé flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people, such a natural disaster, such as Hurricane Katrina, which sets the tone.
When cannon strikes resound in the distance, and you are a mother at home, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, not even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been exacerbated by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor from the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly taken from previously published memoirs, letters, and other documents.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most deal with deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on replacement food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed in sheep's fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made with dried roots and ground apple-dried skin; soles of wooden shoes."
He states that "837 authorised substitute meats are recorded in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories deal with honor and courage.
An American recognizes his own drive towards the wilderness and declares about the war: "You feel that after all, that's what men were meant to do, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper and a bestseller.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is at high risk of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention to him.
“When one is resigned to sacrificing oneself, one hopes to have an audience,” he writes.
It is, unfortunately, quite similar to "a man convicted in secret".
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
“The conflict is becoming more and more a story of economic competition,” writes Peter Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the early century's livestock: the well articulated and ideologically convinced mass murderer, in well-cut clothes, who runs his butchery while sitting behind a counter."
People act in unexpected ways; there are as many basic behaviors as there are heroism.
Peter Englund talks about soldiers who have tried at all costs to catch a venereal disease among prostitutes in order to avoid service at the front.
“We find the most grotesque expression in the pus trade due to gonorrhea, which soldiers buy and spread on the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital,” he writes.
“The most desperate apply it to the eyes, which translates into a lifetime of blindness.”
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Peter Englund’s prose is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly adapted to his task of humanity.
In dozens of short scenes, he captures the way war has "triggered exclusively uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, a social revolution, an aversion to religion."
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are making them war.
The best works dealing with the First World War are often indirect, such as Paul Fussel's "Great War and Modern Memory", or Erich Maria Remarque's "To the West nothing new", rather than complete.
Peter Englund's work is an unconventional pantheon.
The end of the book is the most overwhelming I have read in a non-fictional work.
I won't reveal it.
But it's as if he's come out of his book, grab this page with your hands and burn it with a lightbulb.
