Walls Have Eyes: Researchers Study You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was a simple guy who shared his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having been caught in a murderous madness in Norway in July leaving 77 victims, was faced with his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time prior to the attack on his computer, discussing with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Connect to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t so difficult to find them,” said Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by DEMOS’ think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific precision — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett’s team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to an investigation. The questions asked were about their level of rape and the level of rape they had.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way to do research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young people and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Thinking groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "I like", wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the “supernova of data” is generating an explosion in research, increasing the number of research jobs whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you might not be able to approach on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to investigate the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You should go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in,” says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their feats in a state of ebrition were vastly more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk about alcohol too often.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
“We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not otherwise be recognized.”
