The lie destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has gone on to become an idiot by quickly emitting denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on the tests of the school and the university are legion.
There have been cases where teachers gave the test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to write: "I've had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in deep-rooted psychology and research in prestigious universities.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t get wet, reddish or don’t always get agitated.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate in our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include, amongst other things, the mismanagement of the
Good liars are able to read others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "centred on them" while women say more lies "centred on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than non-married people lie to them than they do to their partners.
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is called "setting the reference data".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves his feet constantly so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see him move his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal misleading behaviors.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change posture significantly, or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all issues are not difficult.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson snagged using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Fraudulent individuals may also use a distant language: "I have not had sexual relations with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or completely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember goods... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
