Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed of technocrats in his majority, although it is unclear when the new executive will assume his post.
Monti said he was going to present the president with the result of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
The “frame is now well-trodden,” he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in less time than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
