“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts will have a good result,” said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocrat majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers’ groups and youth and women’s organizations on Monday.
He will finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was named on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over the new prime minister’s success.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for Eurozone’s current financial defences.
Monti said his government should continue until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are over.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
