MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Social Insurance Leads Investigation to Discover the Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; This Is Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called the "Children and Adolescent Obesity Genetics" protocol, which will have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital des Specialités of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and third-cycle students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation is invited to participate in the rightful or non-rightful population, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is given to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that as of October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research and that of knowing the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and identifying risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their family history of their diseases, to avoid the risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays it will be applied to all participants of anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (the aim is to identify the associated genes).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
