Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and consequently the formation of cracks.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give its viscous support to the carat.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes cracking, ajouta.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on the environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in the majority were covered with a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he says, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, it allows forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, these would spread better, according to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, of the sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the stresses, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to get out, which softens all the layers of the paving and therefore causes cracks.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first that gets lost is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle load is another important factor for cassis formation and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent cassis formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cracks easily and without having to use high temperatures.
