Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; it is also a fragile commodity.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the goulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Gre.
Some believed that it would be enough, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
It is known, since Napoleon, "the Little One", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition of it and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, the Light, economic and social solidarity, a justice.
The crisis of Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, and first of all, a crisis of politics and democracy.
In this respect, the palinody of the true and false Greek referendum will have had the value of twofold revelation: that of the need for a powerful return from politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, the Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a dispersed order.
A white-singing to the absolute European monarch or a leap on foot together in the void of nationalist reprisal: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but a common exercise of full right, peaceful and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we can no longer stop the listing - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that adheres to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the management of the European project.
For it is together that the Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare the future by investing.
The crisis will involve decisions at European level that cannot be made without full democratic legitimacy, except, of course, to lead us to disaster.
After fighting this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors for a long time, everyone today demands the European economic government.
Let's go.
But to think without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We need to take a new step in European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" the Republicans.
The revolution in the interests was not enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more integrated Europe economically.
This can only be done by building a more democratic Europe politically, a true European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
