The Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia by passing to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brightly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the valve steering wheel commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via a first 1,224 km tube connecting the Saint Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is due to be completed at the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and in time of this huge project has an air of victory.
The project had been heavily contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Therefore, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by providing its support to this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But this is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are declining.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it’s a new artery that binds us organically,” Fillon confirmed by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating just how politically and economically large gas contracts are.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, who are in number in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of cast concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by precaution,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which does not interfere with its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project officials gave up on it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state company establish permanently off their coast.
“In case of an accident, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the state of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, carried by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, it provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, all of its gas transportation capacity.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by the shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get back into their fees, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012 it will be 6 million.
