Why is the unemployment rate for workers with disabilities still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of persons with disabilities opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy in place in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Disheartening?
“No,” said Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of people with disabilities.
" The progress made in the last fifteen years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
“There’s still a lot to do.”
It must be said that for the disabled, there are many obstacles to access to employment.
They are quite old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it uniquely difficult to return to work, and that "constitute the knot of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
This is for the objective brakes.
The unsaid remains, the mindsets that are evolving, certainly, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise for the City association indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of wheelchair users, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of workers with disabilities, set out in a... 1987 law.
The last known figures, which date from 2008, account for a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed " establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also translates to a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ workers with disabilities, compared with 82 per cent of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
